rage. However, developers are emphasizing focusing on active classes. I need to refine the tests to ensure proper coverage reporting.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Troubleshooting coverage issues**\\\\n\\\\nThe report shows the test is passing, but something seems off. It might not have run in the JVM when the dynamic report was generated, though I think it did. The call site may have null lines that aren’t covered, and I’m contemplating using a Jacoco report instead. The library's bytecode is fixed, so I can't change that. I might create a workaround within the test to improve reporting, but it's challenging because of the anonymous class. I need to approach this task carefully!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Investigating class coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI’m trying to figure out how to get coverage details for the anonymous inner class Opaque$1 through dynamic API usage. Unfortunately, using a debug-compiled Bouncy Castle library isn't an option. It seems like adding a test using Opaque.getValue in a named subclass isn't feasible either due to the anonymous class situation. I’m thinking that the Jacoco XML doesn’t show the source file for Opaque.java, but it recognizes class coverage. Maybe configuring Gradle to include source directories could solve the missing line issue!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_02OVrpEinwNVYyRz7dWnDmuI|fc_0ecf577e0df83e1c0169fbba5e0c788192af3fe059813ff256\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.bouncycastle/bcutil-jdk18on/1.77 -type f -name '*.jar' -printf '%p\\\\n'\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 459, \"output\": 578, \"cacheRead\": 46080, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 47117, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778104913429, \"responseId\": \"resp_0ecf577e0df83e1c0169fbba5263e881928a5186bbd885a834\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_02OVrpEinwNVYyRz7dWnDmuI|fc_0ecf577e0df83e1c0169fbba5e0c788192af3fe059813ff256\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"/home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.bouncycastle/bcutil-jdk18on/1.77/de3eaef351545fe8562cf29ddff4a403a45b49b7/bcutil-jdk18on-1.77.jar\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1778104926467}]}\n4872:[thinking] **Evaluating coverage reporting**\n4874:[thinking] I need to ensure that the call site is covered if a line exists. Should I add a failure check after the `getMethod` call? It looks like the `Method#invoke` was successful. In Jacoco, the `Opaque$1.run` shows that 31 were covered while 15 were missed, specifically in the catch block — which is good. If the report shows raw frames with no lines, then there's no way to follow up. Maybe call sites are still covered if the `sourceKey` is “Unknown Source”?\n4880:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating coverage reporting**\\n\\nI need to ensure that the call site is covered if a line exists. Should I add a failure check after the `getMethod` call? It looks like the `Method#invoke` was successful. In Jacoco, the `Opaque$1.run` shows that 31 were covered while 15 were missed, specifically in the catch block — which is good. If the report shows raw frames with no lines, then there's no way to follow up. Maybe call sites are still covered if the `sourceKey` is “Unknown Source”?\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0ecf577e0df83e1c0169fbba67a6988192b7389f04d7915853\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-7p31SHOILSMg6Fzs7ojCMCzm-GDGAO6tG5F73loxblPPRt0QoyfTPrmSWBov0MvW0dKPqC4jA35tt109_QGCdgeTXRUxnp6VIZSR0GTrD_hUlajkWoyqnA7QMhObtkw2X6je9cFw7QgqGk6ICvIwDFSzE8_6zcc2bpKfXiI7v